text: (1)​Tension(stress) Headache ( Location : Head)
Overview :
https://www.singhealth.com.sg/rhs/news/patient-care/when-is-a-headache-a-
migraine
This is the most common form of headaches. Symptoms are more commonly generalized but can also be
localized to certain parts of the head. Tension headaches are often related to stress, dehydration , muscle
tension or strain. Tension headaches can be episodic or chronic.
Symptoms :
Generalized or band-like headache , tension around neck
Red flags :
Localized neurological deficits such as weakness (paralysis) , numbness , facial droop, speech difficulty ,
vision changes , elevated blood pressure .
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and/or physical exam. Imaging studies can be helpful to
confirm diagnosis.
Treatment :
Ibuprofen 600 - 800mg
Adequate hydration
Causes :
Physical or mental stress, muscle sprain , muscle spasms , dehydration
Prevention:
Adequate hydration , Rest , adequate amount of sleep , exercise , practice good neck posture
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)
Do you have any of these symptoms Localized neurological changes or stroke like symptoms
such as weakness (paralysis) , numbness , facial droop, speech difficulty , vision changes , severely
elevated blood pressure ( systolic blood pressure > 180 mmhg , diastolic blood pressure > 100
mmhg )
Do you have any of these conditions chronic kidney disease , stomach ulcers
Are you taking blood thinners such warfarin, eliquis, pradaxa , plavix

(2)​ Viral (acute) Sinusitis : ( Location : HEAD)
https://pharmeasy.in/blog/home-remedies-for-sinus-problems/
Overview :
Viral sinusitis, also known as acute viral rhinosinusitis, is a common condition characterized by inflammation of the sinuses,
which are air-filled cavities in the skull. This inflammation is usually caused by a viral infection, such as the common cold
or influenza
Symptoms :
Nasal congestion , facial pain, facial pressure , runny nose , coughing, fatigue , headache . Symptoms are typically
present for less than 7-10 days .
Red flags :
Persistent fever, severe pain, confusion or altered mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and/or physical exam. Imaging studies can be helpful to
confirm diagnosis.
Treatment :
Ibuprofen 600- 800mg
Prednisone 40 mg daily
Adequate hydration and rest are essential to support the body’s immune response and aid recovery.
Causes :
Viral infections originating from the upper respiratory tract. Common viruses include rhinoviruses, influenza viruses, and
adenoviruses.
Prevention:
Regular hand washing , avoid close contact with individuals suffering from a respiratory infection , vaccination against
influenza and covid-19
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)
Do you have any of these symptoms Persistent fever, severe pain, confusion or altered mental
status
Do you have any of these conditions chronic kidney disease , stomach ulcers
Are you taking blood thinners such warfarin, eliquis, pradaxa , plavix

(3) Bacterial (acute) Sinusitis : ( Location : HEAD)
https://pharmeasy.in/blog/home-remedies-for-sinus-problems/
Overview :
Bacterial sinusitis, also known as acute bacterial rhinosinusitis, is a condition characterized by the inflammation of the
sinuses, typically due to a bacterial infection. It often develops as a complication of a viral upper respiratory infection or
persists after a viral sinusitis.
Symptoms :
Prolonged symptoms > 7-10 days , persistent discharge , yellowish - greenish discharge , fever , worsening symptoms
after initial improvement , facial pain, facial pressure , headache . .
Red flags :
Persistent fever, Intractable pain, confusion or altered mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and/or physical exam . Imaging studies can be helpful to
confirm diagnosis .
Treatment :
Ibuprofen 600 - 800mg
Oral Antibiotics : Augmentin 875-125mg , clindamycin 300mg
Adequate hydration and rest are essential to support the body’s immune response and aid recovery.
Causes :
Bacterial Infections by pathogens such such as Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae, and Moraxella
catarrhalis. Infection may follow after a recent viral upper respiratory infection, which damages the mucous membranes,
making it easier for bacteria to invade.
Prevention:
Regular hand washing , avoid close contact with individuals suffering from a respiratory infection , vaccination against
influenza and covid-19
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)
Do you have any of these symptoms Persistent fever, severe pain, confusion or altered mental status
Do you have any of these conditions chronic kidney disease , stomach ulcers

(4) Tooth Infection (Dental Abscess) : ( Location : HEAD /MOUTH)
https://familydentistnashua.com/factors-that-can-lead-to-dental-pain
Overview :
Tooth infections can be described as the product of inflammatory processes in structures surrounding the teeth and
gums. The associated pain can be moderate to severe . If not promptly treated, tooth infections can lead to serious
complications that require immediate medical attention. .The definitive treatment will be removal of the source of
infection . .
Symptoms :
The most common symptom is pain. Other symptoms include gum swelling, foul odor, foul taste in mouth , fever, facial
swelling , inability to open mouth.
Red flags :
Persistent fever, Intractable pain, facial swelling, drooling, inability to open mouth, confusion or altered mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and/or physical exam.
Treatment :
Ibuprofen as needed every 6-8 hours alternate with Tylenol as needed every 6-8 hours
Antibiotics : Augmentin twice a day for 10 days , clindamycin every 8 hrs for 7 days
Causes :
Poor dental hygiene , Untreated cavities/ tooth decay, Gum disease , Dental trauma, weakened immune system ,
foreign object lodged in teeth or gum, failed dental procedures , impacted teeth .
Prevention:
Brushing and flossing regularly , proper dental hygiene, avoiding smoking / tobacco products, use of fluoride , prompt
treatment of dental issues ,regular dental check ups, Healthy diet .

(5) Pharyngitis (non strep sore throat) : ( HEAD /THROAT )
https://my-doc.com/category/upper-respiratory-infection/page/2/
Overview :
Pharyngitis (sore throat) is defined as inflammation due to an infection of the pharynx / throat. The most common cause of pharyngitis is
viral infections . Other causes include bacterial infections , exposure to irritants such as tobacco , allergies , acid reflux . Pharyngitis is
typically self limiting , lasting 7-10 days. . Viral pharyngitis is highly contagious and can spread easily in crowded places or among close
contacts Bacterial Pharyngitis can be more severe and requires antibiotic treatment . NON- BACTERIAL PHARYNGITIS DOES NOT REQUIRE
ANTIBIOTIC TREATMENT.
Bacterial pharyngitis can be differentiated from viral pharyngitis by a confirmatory test ( strep test) or by symptoms . In bacterial
pharyngitis there is the ABSENCE of cold like symptoms such as headache , coughing , sinus pain , nasal congestion , running nose, pink
eye ( conjunctivitis) .
Symptoms :
Sore throat , swollen tonsils , fever, hoarse voice , cough , difficulty swallowing, runny nose, body aches.
Red flags :
Persistent fever, Intractable pain, inability to open mouth, confusion or altered mental status , difficulty
swallowing/drooling, muffled/hoarse voice, neck swelling, inability to lie flat , confusion / altered mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and/or physical exam.
Treatment :
Throat lozenges
NSAIDS (such as Ibuprofen, Naproxen) as needed every 6-8 hours alternate with Tylenol as needed every 6-8
hours
Short course of steroids
Adequate hydration and rest are essential to support the body’s immune response and aid recovery.
Causes :
Commonly caused by viruses such as Rhinovirus ( RSV ) , Coronoavirus
Prevention:
Brushing and flossing regularly , proper dental hygiene, avoiding smoking / tobacco products, use of fluoride , prompt
treatment of dental issues ,regular dental check ups, Healthy diet .
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)
Do you have any of these symptoms Persistent fever, Intractable pain, inability to open mouth,
confusion or altered mental status , difficulty swallowing/drooling, muffled/hoarse voice, neck
swelling, inability to lie flat , confusion / altered mental status

(6) Strep Pharyngitis ( Strep Throat ) : ( Location : HEAD / THROAT)
https://my-doc.com/category/upper-respiratory-infection/page/2/
Overview :
Strep pharyngitis, commonly referred to as strep throat, is a type of pharyngitis caused by group A Streptococcus bacteria (Streptococcus
pyogenes). It is a highly contagious infection that affects the throat and tonsils.
Symptoms :
Sore throat , swollen tonsils , fever, enlarged lymph nodes , tonsillar exudate headache .
Red flags :
Persistent fever, Intractable pain, inability to open mouth, confusion or altered mental status , difficulty
swallowing/drooling, muffled/hoarse voice, neck swelling, inability to lie flat , confusion / altered mental status .
Diagnosis : Diagnosis can be made through a combination of clinical evaluation and laboratory testing. A rapid strep test, which
involves swabbing the back of the throat to detect the presence of streptococcal bacteria is most commonly used in making a diagnosis.
In some cases, a throat culture may be performed to confirm the diagnosis.
In situations where laboratory testing is unavailable, the decision to treat with antibiotics can be made based on recent exposure to sick
contacts with confirmed diagnosis of strep throat (pharyngitis) . Diagnosis can also be made based on age and clinical symptoms such as
presence of fever , absence of cough , presence of painful/enlarged neck lymph nodes and tonsillar exudates .
Treatment :
Throat lozenges
NSAIDS (such as Ibuprofen, Naproxen) as needed every 6-8 hours alternate with Tylenol as needed every 6-8 hours
Antibiotics : Augmentin twice a day for 10 days , clindamycin every 8 hrs for 7 days , azithromycin daily for 5 days .
Adequate hydration and rest are essential to support the body’s immune response and aid recovery.
Causes : Strep throat is caused by infection with group A Streptococcus bacteria. These bacteria are highly contagious and are
commonly transmitted through respiratory droplets when an infected person coughs, sneezes, or talks. The bacteria can also spread
through direct contact with contaminated surfaces or objects.
Prevention
Preventing the spread of strep pharyngitis involves practicing good hygiene, such as frequent handwashing, covering
the mouth and nose when coughing or sneezing, and avoiding close contact with individuals who are sick. Prompt
diagnosis and treatment of strep throat can also help prevent the spread of infection to others.
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)

confusion or altered mental status , difficulty swallowing/drooling, muffled/hoarse voice, neck
swelling, inability to lie flat , confusion / altered mental status .

(7) Otitis externa / swimmer's ear : ( LOCATION : HEAD/EAR)
https://www.verywellhealth.com/fungal-ear-infection-5185077
Overview :
Otitis refers to inflammation or infection of the ear, and it can affect different parts of the ear, including the outer ear
(otitis externa), middle ear (otitis media), and inner ear (otitis interna) . Otitis externa, also known as swimmer's ear, is an
infection of the outer ear canal. It is often caused by water getting trapped in the ear, creating a moist environment for
bacteria or fungi to grow. Recent history of swimming , complete immersion in a tub or frequent long use of
headphones .
Symptoms :
Ear pain, itching, redness, swelling of the ear canal, discharge, and hearing loss.
Red flags :
Persistent fever, Intractable pain, dizziness or poor balance, confusion or altered mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and/or physical exam.
Treatment :
NSAIDS (such as Ibuprofen, Naproxen) as needed every 6-8 hours alternate with Tylenol as needed every 6-8 hours
Antibiotics + corticosteroid combination : Ciprofloxacin-dexamethasone (Ciprodex) 4 drops in the affected ear(s) every 12
hours. , Ciprofloxacin-hydrocortisone (Cipro HC) 3 drops in the affected ear(s) every 12 hours.
Causes :
Exposure to water , bacterial or fungal infection , foreign object in ear , skin conditions such as psoriasis and eczema .
Prevention
Dry ears thoroughly after swimming or taking a bath , avoid inserting objects in ear, wearing ear protection when
swimming .
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)
Do you have any of these symptoms Persistent fever, Intractable pain, dizziness or poor balance, confusion or
altered mental status
Do you have any of these conditions chronic kidney disease , stomach ulcers
Are you taking blood thinners such warfarin, eliquis, pradaxa , plavix

(8) Otitis media : ( Location : HEAD/EAR)
Overview :
Otitis refers to inflammation or infection of the ear, and it can affect different parts of the ear, including the outer ear
(otitis externa), middle ear (otitis media), and inner ear (otitis interna) . Otitis media is an inflammatory or infectious
condition affecting the middle ear, the space behind the eardrum . It most commonly occurs as a complication of a
viral upper respiratory infection .
Symptoms :
Ear pain, fever, drainage from ear , irritability , hearing loss, feeling of fullness or pressure in the ear.
Red flags :
Persistent fever, Intractable pain, dizziness or poor balance, confusion or altered mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and/or physical exam.
Treatment :
NSAIDS (such as Ibuprofen, Naproxen) as needed every 6-8 hours alternate with Tylenol as needed every 6-8 hours
Antibiotics : Augmentin twice a day for 10 days , clindamycin every 8 hrs for 7 days , azithromycin daily for 5 days .
Causes :
Bacterial or viral infection, eustachian tube dysfunction , allergies , exposure to tobacco smoke
Prevention:
Vaccination against influenza and pneumococus , good hygiene such as hand washing , avoiding exposure to
tobacco smoke

(9) Bacterial Conjunctivitis ( Eye infection , pink eye): ( Location : HEAD/EYES)
https://www.sciencephoto.com/media/256621/view/inflamed-eyes-caused-by-conjunctivitis
Overview :
Bacterial conjunctivitis, often called bacterial pink eye, is an eye infection caused by bacteria. It affects the conjunctiva, a thin layer of
tissue covering the white part of your eye and the inside of your eyelids.
Symptoms :
Pain, Eye redness , grittiness , eye discharge (copious amount) , itchiness , tearing , crusting
Red flags :
Persistent fever, Intractable pain ,loss of vision, confusion or altered mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and/or physical exam.
Treatment :
NSAIDS (such as Ibuprofen, Naproxen) as needed every 6-8 hours alternate with Tylenol as needed every 6-8 hours
Topical Antibiotics :
Non-contact lens users : Erythromycin ophthalmic ointment: Apply a 1 cm ribbon to the affected eye(s) every 6 hours
for 7 days OR, Trimethoprim-polymyxin B 0.1%-10,000 U/mL ophthalmic solution: Administer 1 drop to the affected
eye(s) every 3 hours for up to a maximum of 6 doses per 24 hours for 7-10 days ,
Contact Lens users : Moxifloxacin 0.5% ophthalmic solution: Administer 1 drop to the affected eye(s) every 8 hours
for 7 days OR Ciprofloxacin 0.3% ophthalmic solution: Administer 1-2 drops to the affected eye(s) every 2 hours while
the patient is awake on days 1 and 2, then 1-2 drops every 4 hours while the patient is awake on days 3 to 7
Causes :
Bacterial conjunctivitis occurs when harmful bacteria enter the eye, leading to an infection. These bacteria can be transmitted through
direct contact with contaminated surfaces, touching the eye with unwashed hands, or sharing personal items like towels or makeup with
someone who has bacterial conjunctivitis.
Prevention:
Wash your hands frequently, especially before touching your eyes or face . Avoid sharing towels, pillows, or makeup with others, especially
if they have bacterial conjunctivitis. If you wear contact lenses, follow proper hygiene practices and avoid wearing them if your eyes are
irritated or infected.
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)
Do you have any of these symptoms Persistent fever, Intractable pain ,loss of vision, confusion or altered mental
status
** Antibiotics eye drop/ointment

Instructions

Drink plenty water to achieve adequate hydration
OR
(L)​ Ciprofloxacin ophthalmic 0.3% , 5ml ( Contact lens users )
Instructions
Apply 1-2 drops every 2 hours for 2 days while awake , 1-2 drops every 4 hours from day 3-7
Avoid use of contacts during treatment, and for at least 1 week after symptoms resolve
Drink plenty water to achieve adequate hydration
(10) Cold sores : ( Location : HEAD/MOUTH)
https://www.everydayhealth.com/cold-sores/symptoms-diagnosis/
Overview :
A fever blister, also known as a cold sore, is a common condition caused by the herpes simplex virus 1 (HSV-1) . Less commonly, they
can also be caused by herpes simplex virus type 2 (HSV-2), especially through oral-genital contact.
The Initial Infection (Primary HSV infection) may cause no symptoms or mild flu-like symptoms. In some cases, painful blisters or ulcers can
develop on the lips, mouth, or gums along with fever and swollen lymph nodes.Recurrent Infections may occur after the initial infections.
HSV remains dormant in nerve cells and can periodically reactivate, leading to recurrent outbreaks. Recurrent fever blisters typically start
with tingling, burning, or itching sensations (prodrome) followed by the appearance of fluid-filled blisters that crust over within a few days.
Symptoms :
Pain, fluid filled blisters,, tingling, burning, itching, painful/enlarged lymph nodes
Red flags :
Persistent fever, Intractable pain , rash surrounding or involving eye, confusion or altered mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and/or physical exam.
Treatment :
Early initiation of treatment during prodromal symptoms or at the onset of lesions is most effective
Oral antiviral medications like acyclovir, valacyclovir, and famciclovir are commonly prescribed to reduce the severity and
duration of fever blister outbreaks.
Valacyclovir 2000mg
Famciclovir 500mg
Acyclovir 400mg
Over-the-counter or prescription topical antiviral creams may also be used for symptomatic relief and to speed up healing
Acyclovir 5% cream 6 times a day for 7 days
Causes :
Cold sores are highly contagious and can be spread through close contact with an infected person, such as kissing or sharing utensils ,
towels, or razors. Recurrent infections can be caused by triggers such as stress , fatigue , hormonal changes such as menstruation , sun
exposure and certain foods .Bacterial conjunctivitis occurs when harmful bacteria enter the eye, leading to an infection. These bacteria
can be transmitted through direct contact with contaminated surfaces, touching the eye with unwashed hands, or sharing personal items
like towels or makeup with someone who has bacterial conjunctivitis.
Prevention:
avoid close contact, kissing, or sharing personal items to prevent spreading HSV to others.
Sunscreen or lip balms with SPF can help prevent sun-induced outbreaks.
Stress reduction techniques and maintaining overall good health can help reduce the frequency of fever blister
outbreaks in some individuals.
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)

confusion or altered mental status
Did your symptoms begin more than 72 hours ago

(11) Bronchitis (Non-bacterial) : ( Location : CHEST/LUNGS)
https://www.istockphoto.com/photo/suffering-from-cold-gm890971480-246789586
Overview :
Bronchitis is inflammation of the bronchi or lower respiratory tract. Acute Bronchitis is commonly caused by viruses, such as the common
cold or flu viruses. It often resolves on its own within a few weeks. It can also be caused by extended exposure to irritants such as
cigarette smoke, vaping , hookah, air pollution, dust, or chemical fumes.
Symptoms :
Coughing and wheezing . Symptoms related to viral illnesses such as sore throat , low grade fever, chest discomfort , body aches, runny
nose and mild headache may also be present .
Red flags :
Persistent fever, bloody mucus , persistent chest pain , persistent shortness of breath, leg swelling , confusion or altered
mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and/or physical exam.
Treatment :
Bronchitis is commonly caused by viruses, symptoms usually last for 5-7 days and resolves on its own with rest, adequate
hydration
Avoid irritants such as cigarette smoke, vaping , hookah, air pollution, dust, or chemical fumes.
Symptomatic treatment should be considered when symptoms are severe / unbearable or last longer than 5-7 days.
Symptomatic treatment include
Cough suppressants for persistent coughing
Albuterol inhaler and as needed for wheezing
Short course of steroids such as prednisone for 5 days
Causes :
Acute bronchitis is commonly caused by viral infections, including rhinovirus, influenza virus, and respiratory syncytial virus (RSV). Extended
exposure to irritants such as cigarette smoke, vaping , hookah, air pollution, dust, or chemical fumes.
Prevention:
Practice good hand hygiene, especially during cold and flu seasons, to reduce the risk of viral infections.
Avoiding Irritants: Quit smoking and minimize exposure to lung irritants such as secondhand smoke, air pollutants, and
occupational chemicals.
Annual flu vaccination and pneumococcal vaccination can help prevent respiratory infections.
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)
Do you have any of these symptoms Persistent fever, bloody mucus , persistent chest pain , persistent shortness
of breath, leg swelling , confusion or altered mental status

(12) Bronchitis (Bacterial) : ( Location : CHEST/LUNGS)
https://www.nyworkerslaw.com/social-security-disability-respiratory-disorders-in-nyc/
Overview :
Bronchitis is inflammation of the bronchi or lower respiratory tract caused by a bacterial infection. Bacterial bronchitis is typically caused
by bacterial pathogens such as Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae, Moraxella catarrhalis, and occasionally
Mycoplasma pneumoniae or Chlamydophila pneumoniae. Bacterial infections can occur on their own or follow a viral respiratory
infection.
Symptoms :
Cough is productive with yellow to greenish mucus ( sputum) , moderate to high grade fever, chest discomfort , shortness of breath .
Red flags :
Persistent fever, bloody mucus , persistent chest pain , persistent shortness of breath, leg swelling , confusion or altered
mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and/or physical exam.
Treatments
Oral antibiotics
Z-pak/Azithromycin 250-500mg daily for 5 days
Doxycycline 100mg twice a day for 5-7 days
Short course of steroids : prednisone 40mg daily
Symptomatic treatment should be considered when symptoms are severe / unbearable. Symptomatic treatment include
Cough suppressants for persistent coughing
Albuterol inhaler and as needed for wheezing
Adequate hydration and rest are essential to support the body’s immune response and aid recovery.
Causes :
Bacterial bronchitis is caused by bacterial pathogens such as Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae, Moraxella catarrhalis,
and occasionally Mycoplasma pneumoniae or Chlamydophila pneumoniae. Bacterial infections can also occur after a prolonged viral
infection.
Prevention:
Practice good respiratory hygiene, such as covering your mouth and nose when coughing or sneezing, and regular
handwashing to prevent the spread of infections.
Avoiding Irritants: Quit smoking and minimize exposure to lung irritants such as secondhand smoke, air pollutants, and
occupational chemicals.
Annual flu vaccination and pneumococcal vaccination can help prevent respiratory infections.

(13) Asthma Flare up (Asthma attack) : (Location CHEST/LUNGS)
https://www.elsdalestreetsurgery.nhs.uk/news
Overview :
Asthma is a chronic respiratory condition characterized by inflammation and narrowing of the airways, leading to difficulty breathing. It
affects people of all ages and can range from mild to severe .
An asthma attack, also known as an asthma exacerbation, is a sudden worsening of asthma symptoms caused by the tightening of
muscles around the airways (bronchospasm). During an asthma attack, the lining of the airways becomes swollen or inflamed, and thicker
mucus is produced. This can result in difficulty breathing, wheezing, coughing, and chest tightness.
Symptoms :
Difficulty breathing, wheezing, coughing, and chest tightness.
Red flags :
Persistent shortness of breath, bloody mucus , persistent chest pain , persistent fever, confusion or altered mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on medical history, presenting symptoms and/or physical exam.
Treatment :
Acute ( quick relief) management
Albuterol inhaler and as needed for wheezing
Short course of oral corticosteroids for severe symptoms
Avoid triggers
Causes :
Asthma exacerbation ( attacks) are caused by triggers such as
Allergens: Pollen, dust mites, pet dander, mold, etc.
iIrritants: Smoke, pollution, strong odors, chemical fumes.
Respiratory infections: Colds, flu, sinus infections.
Physical activity: Exercise-induced asthma.
Weather conditions: Cold air, changes in weather.
Stress and strong emotions: Anxiety, stress, laughter, crying.
Certain medications: Beta-blockers, aspirin, NSAIDs.
Prevention:
Asthma action plan: A personalized plan created with a healthcare provider to manage asthma, avoid triggers, and
know what to do in case of an attack.
Avoiding triggers: Identifying and avoiding known triggers can reduce the frequency and severity of attacks
Allergen Control: Minimize exposure to known allergens through measures such as using air filters, keeping the home
clean, and avoiding pets if allergic.
Avoid Smoking: Avoid smoking and exposure to secondhand smoke.
Vaccinations: Get vaccinated against influenza and pneumonia to prevent respiratory infections.
Regular Check-ups: Regular visits to your healthcare provider to monitor and manage asthma effectively.

confusion or altered mental status

(14) Gastroenteritis / Food poisoning : ( Location : ABDOMEN / G.I )
https://www.istockphoto.com/photos/catarrh-a
Overview :
Gastroenteritis is an inflammation of the gastrointestinal tract, involving both the stomach and the intestine. It is characterized by a
combination of symptoms including diarrhea, vomiting, abdominal pain, fever and cramping. Gastroenteritis can be caused by various
infectious agents, toxins, and other non-infectious conditions
Symptoms :
Diarrhea , Nausea , vomiting, Abdominal pain and cramps, fever , body aches , dehydration
Red flags :
Bloody stool, persistent fever, inability to tolerate oral / fluid intake, signs of severe dehydration such as low blood pressure or decreased
urine output
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on medical history, presenting symptoms and/or physical exam. Stool and blood tests can be used to
confirm infectious causes.
Treatment :
Pharmacologic Therapy:
Antidiarrheals / Antimotility: Loperamide may be used in adults but is contraindicated in children and in
certain infectious causes of diarrhea.
Antiemetics such as Ondansetron can be used to control vomiting, particularly in children.
Antibiotics are Indicated for specific bacterial infections (e.g., Shigella, severe Campylobacter, C.
difficile).
Encourage feeding and increased fluid intake
Avoid avoid high fat and high sugar foods
Causes :
Infectious Causes:
Bacterial: Salmonella, Shigella, Campylobacter, E. coli, C. difficile.
Viral: Norovirus, rotavirus, adenovirus.
Parasitic: Giardia, Entamoeba histolytica, Cryptosporidium.
Non-Infectious Causes:
Inflammatory: Inflammatory bowel disease (Crohn’s disease, ulcerative colitis).
Malabsorption: Celiac disease, lactose intolerance, pancreatic insufficiency.
Medications: Antibiotics, laxatives, chemotherapy.
Irritable bowel syndrome.
Prevention:
Regular handwashing, especially after using the toilet and before eating.
Proper cooking, handling, and storage of food.
Vaccination: Rotavirus vaccine for infants.
Safe Drinking Water: Ensuring water is clean and treated.

STI Exposure (Location : GENITAL / URINARY System)
https://www.ettaatlantic.com/preventing-stroke-power-of-lifestyle-choices/
Sexually transmitted diseases (STDs), also known as sexually transmitted infections (STIs), are infections that are primarily spread through
sexual contact. These infections can affect anyone who is sexually active and can have a range of health impacts, from mild to severe,
including long-term complications and increased risk of certain cancers and infertility.
Causes :
Bacterial STDs
Chlamydia: Caused by Chlamydia trachomatis. It is often asymptomatic but can cause urethritis, cervicitis, pelvic
inflammatory disease (PID), and infertility.
Gonorrhea: Caused by Neisseria gonorrhoeae. It can lead to urethritis, cervicitis, PID, epididymitis, and disseminated
gonococcal infection.
Syphilis: Caused by Treponema pallidum. Presents in stages: primary (chancre), secondary (rash), latent, and tertiary
(gummas, cardiovascular and neurological complications).
Viral STDs:
Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV): Leads to acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS) if untreated.
Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV): Causes genital herpes, characterized by painful vesicular lesions.
Human Papillomavirus (HPV): Causes genital warts and is linked to cervical, penile, and oropharyngeal cancers.
Hepatitis B and C: Can be sexually transmitted and lead to chronic liver disease and cancer.
Parasitic STDs:
Trichomoniasis: Caused by Trichomonas vaginalis, often asymptomatic in men, can cause vaginal discharge, itching,
and dysuria in women.
Symptoms :
General Symptoms may include unusual genital discharge, sores or warts on the genital area, painful urination, itching, bloody
urine and abdominal pain.
Specific Symptoms:
Chlamydia and Gonorrhea: Often asymptomatic but can cause genital discharge and pelvic pain.
Syphilis: Chancre sores, rashes, and systemic symptoms in later stages.
Herpes: Painful blisters or sores on the genitals or mouth.
HPV: Genital warts and potential changes in the cervix detectable by Pap smear.
Trichomoniasis: Frothy, greenish vaginal discharge with a strong odor, vaginal itching.
Red flags :
Persistent fever , blood in urine , pelvic / groin pain , unexpected weight loss
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on detailed sexual history, presenting symptoms , physical exam and laboratory testing.
Treatment:
Bacterial Infections:
Chlamydia: Azithromycin or Doxycycline.
Gonorrhea: Ceftriaxone plus Azithromycin or Doxycycline.
Syphilis: Penicillin G.
Chancroid: Azithromycin, Ceftriaxone.
Mycoplasma Genitalium: Azithromycin or Moxifloxacin.
Viral Infections:
HIV exposure :
Pre-Exposure Prophylaxis (PrEP): For HIV prevention in high-risk individuals.
ii.​
Post-Exposure Prophylaxis (PEP):For potential HIV exposure, to be started within 72 hours.
HIV (confirmed) : Antiretroviral therapy (ART)..
Herpes: Acyclovir, Valacyclovir, Famciclovir.
HPV: No cure for the virus, treatment for warts and monitoring for cancer.
Hepatitis B: Antiviral medications for chronic infection.
Parasitic Infections:
Trichomoniasis: Metronidazole or Tinidazole.
Prevention:
Vaccination: HPV vaccine (Gardasil, Cervarix), Hepatitis B vaccine.
Barrier Protection: Consistent and correct use of condoms and dental dams.
Regular Screening: Especially important for high-risk groups.
Reducing risky behaviors.

(15) Chlamydia Urethritis : ( Location : GENITAL/URINARY)
Overview :
Chlamydia urethritis is an infection of the urethra caused by the bacterium Chlamydia trachomatis. It is one of the most common sexually
transmitted infections (STIs) and can affect both men and women. Early detection and treatment are crucial to prevent complications
and further transmission
Symptoms :
Symptoms typically take 1-3 weeks to manifest , and in some cases you may show no symptoms
Symptoms in Men:
Urethral discharge (often mucoid or clear)
Dysuria (painful urination)
Urethral itching or irritation
It is common to witness no symptoms, with up to 50% of infected men showing no symptoms.
Symptoms in Women:
Often symptomless or may present with mild symptoms.
Discomfort or pain with urination
Increased vaginal discharge
Bleeding in between menstrual cycle or bleeding after sex
Lower abdominal pain
Can progress to pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) if untreated. PID can lead to infertility in women
Red flags :
Persistent fever , blood in urine , severe or chronic pelvic pain
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on detailed sexual history, presenting symptoms , physical exam and laboratory testing.
Treatment :
Antibiotics:
Azithromycin: A single oral dose of 1 gram.
Doxycycline: 100 mg orally twice a day for 7 days.
It is very important that all recent sexual partners should be notified, tested, and treated to prevent reinfection and further
spread.
Causes :
Chlamydia urethritis is an infection of the urethra caused by the bacterium Chlamydia trachomatis .
Prevention:
Barrier Protection: Consistent and correct use of condoms
Regular Screening: Especially important for high-risk groups.
Reducing risky sexual behaviors.

Genital herpes is a common sexually transmitted infection (STI) caused by the herpes simplex virus (HSV), most often HSV-2, although HSV-1

Diagnosis can be made based on detailed sexual history, presenting symptoms , physical exam and laboratory testing.

There is no cure for herpes

Genital herpes is caused by the herpes simplex virus (HSV) , most often HSV-2, although HSV-1 (typically associated with oral herpes) can
also cause genital herpes through oral-genital contact.

Practicing safe sex, including the use of condoms
Avoiding sexual intercourse , kissing or close contact with individuals who have active cold sores

Overview :
Bacterial vaginosis (also known as BV) is the most common cause of vaginal discharge among women of reproductive age. It is
characterized by an imbalance in the vaginal flora, leading to an overgrowth of anaerobic bacteria.

Thin, white or gray vaginal discharge.
Unpleasant "fishy" odor, especially after intercourse.
Vaginal itching or irritation (less common).

Persistent fever , blood in urine , severe or chronic pelvic pain
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on history, presenting symptoms , characteristics of discharge and laboratory testing.

Oral antibiotics Therapy:

Tinidazole 2 g orally once daily for 2 days or 1 g orally once daily for 5 days.
Intravaginal antibiotics Therapy:
Metronidazole gel 0.75%, one full applicator (5 g) intravaginally once daily for 5 days.
Clindamycin cream 2%, one full applicator (5 g) intravaginally at bedtime for 7 days.
Causes :
Bacterial vaginosis is caused by imbalance in the vaginal flora, leading to an overgrowth of bacteria such as Gardnerella vaginalis .
Prevention:
Avoid douching, limit the number of sexual partners, use condoms.
Daily use of oral or vaginal probiotics

(21) UTI : ( Location : GENITAL / URINARY)
Overview :
Urinary tract infections (UTIs) are common infections that can affect any part of the urinary system, including the urethra, bladder, ureters,
and kidneys. They are more prevalent in women but can occur in men and children as well.
Symptoms :
Dysuria (painful urination),
Urinary frequency
Urinary urgency
Pelvic pain
Blood in urine
Cloudy or strong-smelling urine.
Red flags :
Persistent fever or chills , lower back pain, nausea , vomiting , change in mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms , physical exam and laboratory testing ( urinalysis , urine culture) .
Treatment :
Oral Antibiotic options include Nitrofurantoin , trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole , Cefdinir , Augmentin
Causes :
UTI’s are mostly caused by bacteria, particularly Escherichia coli (E. coli), which usually
lives in the bowel.
Sexual activity and catheter use can introduce bacteria to the bladder, causing an
infection.
Holding urine for long periods of time or incomplete bladder emptying can create an
environment for bacterial growth.
Prevention:
Adequate Hydration : Drink plenty of liquids, especially water.
Urinate frequently: Don't hold urine for long periods.
Wipe properly: Wipe from front to back to prevent bacteria from the anus from entering the urethra.
Hygiene: Keep the genital area clean and dry.
Avoid irritants: Avoid using irritating feminine products like douches and powders.

(22) Muscle spasm / Back pain ( Location : BACK / MUSCLE )
Overview :
Lower back pain can range from dull, constant ache to a sudden, sharp pain and can be acute (lasting a few days to weeks) or chronic
(lasting longer than three months). A muscle spasm, also known as a muscle cramp, is an involuntary and often painful contraction of a
muscle or group of muscles. Muscle spasms can occur in any muscle in the body. They can vary in intensity from mild twitches to severe
pain and immobilization .
Symptoms :
Pain: Ranging from a dull ache to a stabbing or shooting sensation.
Limited Mobility: Difficulty standing up straight or moving the back.
Muscle Spasms: Tightening or knots in the muscles.
Radiating Pain: Pain that travels down the leg (sciatica).
Numbness or Tingling
Red flags :
Severe pain , muscle paralysis , inability to walk
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms , physical exam . Imaging and laboratory studies can be useful in identifying
underlying causes.
Treatment :
Medical management
Muscle relaxants such as flexeril , Robaxin
Anti inflammatory agents such as ibuprofen and acetaminophen
Stretching and Massage
Physical therapy
Heat and cold therapy
Hydration and electrolyte replacement
Causes :
Dehydration: Inadequate fluid intake can lead to electrolyte imbalances, causing muscle
cramps.Deficiencies in minerals like potassium, calcium, magnesium, and sodium can trigger spasms.
Overuse or Strain: Excessive exercise, especially without proper warm-up or stretching, can lead to
muscle fatigue and spasms.
Prolonged Inactivity: Staying in one position for too long, such as sitting or standing, can cause
muscles to cramp
Musculoskeletal Conditions such as arthritis , scoliosis, spinal stenosis or bulging / herniated disk
Poor Circulation: Reduced blood flow to muscles, often due to peripheral artery disease, can cause
spasms.
Prevention:
Adequate Hydration : Drink plenty of liquids, especially water.
Urinate frequently: Don't hold urine for long periods.
Wipe properly: Wipe from front to back to prevent bacteria from the anus from entering the urethra.
Hygiene: Keep the genital area clean and dry.
Avoid irritants: Avoid using irritating feminine products like douches and powders

(23) Skin infection ( cellulitis) (Location : SKIN )
Overview :
Cellulitis is an acute bacterial infection of the skin and underlying tissues. It typically affects the outer layer of the skin, leading to
inflammation and potentially severe complications if untreated. Treatment in a timely manner is necessary to prevent complications.
Symptoms :
Redness
Swelling
Warmth
Pain/ Tenderness in the affected area
Fever / Chills ( severe cases )
Red flags :
Persistent fever or chills , confusion or change in mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms and physical exam .
Treatment :
Oral Antibiotic options include Bactrim ( trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole) , Keflex (cephalexin) , Clindamycin
Causes :
Cellulitis is caused by bacteria such as staphylococcus and Streptococcus species, some of which might be normal skin flora . Certain risk
factors increase the risk of cellulitis , these include
Skin breaks: Such as cuts, surgical wounds, or insect bites.
Chronic skin conditions such as Eczema, athlete's foot.
Compromised immune system: conditions such as Diabetes, cancer, HIV/AIDS.
Intravenous drug use
Surgical wounds
Obesity
Foreign Bodies: Splinters, surgical implants.
Prevention:
Proper wound care and hygiene.
Management of Chronic Conditions: Like diabetes , eczema and other chronic skin conditions.
Good Hygiene: Regular hand washing , proper care and hygiene of wounds.
Proper Wound Care: Immediate and adequate treatment of cuts, scratches, and other skin injuries.
Management of Chronic Conditions: Effective control of underlying health conditions that may
predispose to abscess formation.
Avoiding Risk Factors: Proper use of needles

Do you have any of these conditions chronic kidney disease
Are you taking blood thinners such warfarin, eliquis, pradaxa , plavix

Overview :
An abscess is a localized collection of pus within a tissue, usually caused by infection. It results from the body’s inflammatory response to a
bacterial (or fungal pathogen), often leading to a cavity filled with pus and inflammatory cells.

Swelling
Warmth

resolution.

(25) Eczema Flare up : (Loaction: SKIN)
https://stock.adobe.com/search?k=allergy+rash
https://stock.adobe.com/images/itchy-psoriasis-on-arm-and-hand/556111310
Overview :
Eczema, also known as atopic dermatitis, is a chronic inflammatory skin condition characterized by itchy, red, and dry patches of skin. It is
a common condition that often begins in childhood but can occur at any age.
An eczema flare-up is an episode where the symptoms of eczema (atopic dermatitis) worsen significantly. This typically involves increased
redness, swelling, itching, and discomfort in the affected areas of the skin. Flare-ups can vary in severity and duration, and they can be
triggered by various factors.
Symptoms :
Itching, redness, swelling, and dryness
Red flags :
Persistent fever or chills , signs of skin infection , severe or persisting pain .
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on medical history, presenting symptoms and/or physical exam.
Treatment :
Oral Steroids
5 day course of oral corticosteroids such as prednisone
Topical steroids
5-7 day course of topical steroids such as hydrocortisone lotion/ointment
Causes :
Eczema flare ups are caused by triggers such as
Environmental Factors: such as Weather , Pollutants
Irritants : Such as Soaps and Detergents , Fabrics (Rough or scratchy materials) , Personal Care Products
Allergens: Such as Pollen , Pet Dander , Dust Mites
Lifestyle Factors : such as Stress , Diet , Sweat
Prevention:
Asthma action plan: A personalized plan created with a healthcare provider to manage asthma, avoid triggers, and
know what to do in case of an attack.
Avoiding triggers: Identifying and avoiding known triggers can reduce the frequency and severity of attacks
Allergen Control: Minimize exposure to known allergens through measures such as using air filters, keeping the home
clean, and avoiding pets if allergic.
Avoid Smoking: Avoid smoking and exposure to secondhand smoke.
Vaccinations: Get vaccinated against influenza and pneumonia to prevent respiratory infections.
Regular Check-ups: Regular visits to your healthcare provider to monitor and manage asthma effectively.

confusion or altered mental status

(26) COVID-19 infection : ( Location : CHEST / LUNGS)
https://www.istockphoto.com/photo/suffering-from-cold-gm890971480-246789586
Overview :
COVID-19 is an infectious disease caused by the virus SARS-CoV-2. The disease primarily affects the respiratory system but can also impact
various other organs and systems in the body. Transmission is typically person to person as the virus can be spread via respiratory droplets .
Respiratory droplets are expelled when an infected person coughs, sneezes, talks, or breathes. In some settings, particularly indoors with
poor ventilation, tiny droplets or aerosols can remain suspended in the air, potentially leading to airborne transmission. The virus can be
spread via surface contact as the virus can survive on surfaces for varying periods, and transmission can occur if a person touches a
contaminated surface and then touches their face (mouth, nose, or eyes). Individuals who are infected with the virus but do not show
symptoms (asymptomatic) can still spread the virus to others.
Symptoms :
Coughing and wheezing . Symptoms related to viral illnesses such as sore throat , low grade fever, chest discomfort , body aches, runny
nose and mild headache may also be present .
Red flags :
Persistent fever, bloody mucus , persistent chest pain , persistent shortness of breath, leg swelling , confusion or altered mental status
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on presenting symptoms , physical exam and laboratory (or home) tests .
Treatment :
Antiviral Medications: Paxlovid is an antiviral treatment that decreases severity illness and shortens illness course. Paxlovid is
highly recommended for patients who are immunocompromised or have chronic medical conditions such as asthma , COPD ,
heart disease , Type 2 diabetes. Paxlovid prevents disease progression, thereby preventing hospitalization in patients with
mild-moderate disease.
Symptomatic Treatment: Rest, hydration, and over-the-counter medications (such as tylenol and ibuprofen) for fever and pain.
Self-Isolation: Self isolation for 5-7 days from onset of symptoms to prevent spreading the virus to others.
Causes :
COVID_19 infection is a viral illness caused by the novel coronavirus SARS-CoV-2
Prevention:
Vaccination: COVID-19 vaccines are effective in preventing severe illness, hospitalization, and death. Booster doses are
recommended to maintain immunity over time.
Masking: Wearing masks, especially in crowded or indoor settings, helps reduce the spread of the virus.
Hand Hygiene: Regular handwashing with soap and water or using hand sanitizer.
Social Distancing: Keeping a safe distance from others, especially in areas with high transmission rates.
Avoiding Crowded Places and Poorly Ventilated Spaces: To minimize the risk of exposure.
Testing and Quarantine: Testing before and after travel or potential exposure, and following quarantine guidelines if exposed or
symptomatic.
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)
Do you have any of these symptoms Persistent fever, coughing up blood , persistent chest pain , persistent
shortness of breath, leg swelling , confusion or altered mental status

(26) Acid Reflux / Heartburn ( Location : Abdomen / G.I )
https://www.istockphoto.com/photo/suffering-from-cold-gm890971480-246789586
Overview :
Acid reflux, also known as gastroesophageal reflux (GER), occurs when stomach acid or, sometimes, bile flows back into the esophagus.
This backflow, or reflux, irritates the lining of the esophagus and causes a burning sensation in the chest, commonly referred to as
heartburn. Acid reflux is a common condition experienced by many people occasionally, but frequent acid reflux may indicate a more
severe condition known as gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD).
Symptoms :
Heartburn
Regurgitation
Bloating
Burping
Difficulty swallowing or a sensation of food being stuck in the esophagus.
Chronic Cough
Sore Throat and Hoarseness
Nausea
Red flags :
Difficulty swallowing, Black tarry stool, Vomiting blood , Blood in stool, Severe/persistent pain
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on medical history and physical examination. A Gastroenterology consultation and
Endoscopy may be necessary to confirm diagnosis and to assess for complications of GERD / Chronic reflux.
Treatment :
Proton Pump Inhibitors (PPIs): Potent acid blockers that suppress acid production and allow healing of the esophagus
(e.g., omeprazole, esomeprazole). It is indicated for long term management of acid reflux .
H2 Receptor Blockers: Reduce acid production (e.g., ranitidine, famotidine).
Antacids: Provides quick relief by neutralizing stomach acid (e.g., Tums OTC , Maalox OTC )
Causes :
Weak Lower Esophageal Sphincter (LES)
Hiatal Hernia
Obesity
Eating Large Meals
Spicy foods, fatty foods, chocolate, caffeine, alcohol, and acidic foods like citrus and tomatoes can trigger acid
reflux.
Lying Down After Eating
Pregnancy
Certain medications, including NSAIDs, some blood pressure medications, and sedatives, can increase the risk of
acid reflux.
Prevention:
Eat Smaller, More Frequent Meals
Avoid Trigger Foods
Elevate the Head of the Bed
Maintain a Healthy Weight
Quit Smoking
Avoid Lying Down After Meals, Wait at least 2-3 hours after eating before lying down.
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)
Do you have any of these symptoms Difficulty swallowing, Black tarry stool, Vomiting blood , Blood in stool,
Severe/persistent pain

(20) Oral Thrush ( Location : Mouth )
https://www.pharmacyplanet.com/blog/post/how-do-you-treat-vaginal-thrush-overnight
Overview :
Oral thrush, also known as oral candidiasis, is a fungal infection in the mouth caused by an overgrowth of the yeast Candida albicans.
While Candida is a normal inhabitant of the mouth, its overgrowth can lead to the development of oral thrush. This condition is most
commonly seen in infants, older adults, and individuals with weakened immune systems, but it can affect anyone.
Symptoms :
Creamy white lesions on the tongue, inner cheeks, roof of the mouth, gums, or tonsils. These patches may resemble
cottage cheese and can be painful or bleed when scraped.
Redness, soreness, or a burning sensation in the mouth and throat, which can make eating or swallowing
uncomfortable.
Redness, cracking, or soreness at the corners of the mouth
Loss of Taste
Cottony Feeling in the Mouth
Difficulty Swallowing (In Severe Cases)
Red flags :
Persistent fever , Difficulty swallowing, severe pain
Diagnosis :
Diagnosis can be made based on history, presenting symptoms . Laboratory/Microscopic examination can be used for confirmation .
Treatment :
Nystatin mouthwash
Causes :
Weakened Immune System such individuals with HIV/AIDS, cancer, or undergoing
chemotherapy, are more susceptible to oral thrush.
Antibiotic Use
Poorly controlled diabetes
Dry Mouth
Poorly cleaned dentures
Smoking
Use of Inhaled corticosteroids used for asthma or other respiratory conditions
Prevention:
Avoid unnecessary antibiotic use
Well managed diabetes
Rinse mouth thoroughly after use of inhaled corticosteroids
Avoid tobacco use
Good oral hygiene
Proper cleaning of dentures
Avoid excessive intake of sugars and refined carbohydrates
TREATMENT ( TREATMENT PAGE)
Do you have any of these symptoms Persistent fever , Difficulty swallowing, severe pain
** Oral Antifungal
Nystatin (100,000 units/ml) mouthwash (preferred)
Instructions
Swish 4-6ml around mouth and retain as long as possible before swallowing four times daily for 7-10
days
Drink plenty water to achieve adequate hydration
